164. Neth J Med. 2018 Sep;76(7):330-335.

Coronary artery spasms due to tyrosine kinase inhibitors used in chronic myeloid 
leukemia.

Fiets RB(1), Staal AHJ, Cramer GE, Blijlevens NMA.

Author information:
(1)Department of Hematology, Erasmus University Medical Center, Rotterdam, the 
Netherlands.

Tyrosine kinase inhibitors (TKIs) have changed the landscape of treatment for 
patients with chronic myeloid leukemia (CML) leading to a life expectancy 
comparable to the general population. Side effects commonly encountered during 
TKI treatment are pleural effusion due to use of dasatinib and vascular side 
effects due to nilotinib and ponatinib. Coronary artery spasm (CAS), although 
encountered during treatment with other chemotherapeutic drugs, have to our 
knowledge never been reported during TKI treatment. Here, we describe two cases 
of coronary artery spasms which are likely due to TKIs.

