Subcutaneous implantable cardioverter defibrillator in cardiomyopathies and 
channelopathies.

Migliore F(1), Pelliccia F(2), Autore C(3), Bertaglia E(1), Cecchi F(4), Curcio 
A(5), Bontempi L(6), Curnis A(6), De Filippo P(7), D'Onofrio A(8), Francia P(3), 
Maurizi N(9), Musumeci B(3), Proclemer A(10), Zorzi A(1), Corrado D(1).

Author information:
(1)Department of Cardiac, Thoracic and Vascular Sciences, University of Padova.
(2)Department Attilio Reale, Sapienza University.
(3)Department of Clinical and Molecular Medicine, Sapienza University of Rome, 
Rome.
(4)Department of Clinical and Experimental Medicine, University of Florence, 
Florence.
(5)Division of Cardiology, Department of Medical and Surgical Sciences, 
University Magna Graecia, Campus di Germaneto, Catanzaro.
(6)Division of Cardiology, Spedali Civili Hospital, Brescia.
(7)Cardiac Electrophysiology and Pacing Unit, Cardiovascular Department, 
Ospedale Papa Giovanni XXIII, Bergamo.
(8)Department of Cardiology, Monaldi Hospital, AORN Ospedali dei Colli, Naples.
(9)Cardiomyopathy Unit, Careggi University Hospital, Florence.
(10)University Hospital Santa Maria della Misericordia, Udine, Italy.

: Cardiomyopathies and channelopathies are heterogeneous disorders that increase 
the risk of sudden cardiac death (SCD). Implantable cardioverter-defibrillator 
(ICD) therapy is safe and effective for preventing SCD in patients at risk for 
malignant ventricular arrhythmias. Because of the poor positive predictive value 
of current risk stratification tools, the majority of patients implanted with an 
ICD will never receive a life-saving therapy but will be exposed to the risk of 
complications such as device infection, lead failure and inappropriate therapy. 
Subcutaneous ICD (S-ICD) now constitutes a valuable alternative to conventional 
transvenous ICD in patients with cardiomyopathies and channelopathies as it 
provides protection from SCD while avoiding the risks of intravascular lead 
infection or failure. This may be particularly advantageous for young patients 
with a very long life expectancy. On the other hand, S-ICD cannot deliver 
antitachycardia pacing or antibradycardia pacing. The purpose of this article is 
to review the available evidence and the future perspectives of S-ICD therapy in 
patients with cardiomyopathies or channelopathies.

